  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\nYou're building a fan shoutout feature for an artist's website. The artist wants to record a message to shout out a fan by name. Right now, the function always prints the same name, but that needs to change depending on who gets the shoutout.\r\n\r\n1. Look at the function `fan_shoutout()`. Right now, it always prints a message for `\"Jamie\"`.\r\n\r\n2. Add a parameter to the function so the artist can shout out any fan.\r\n\r\n3. Update the print statement to use the parameter.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nA **parameter** is a placeholder in the function definition. When you call the function, you pass in an argument that fills that placeholder.\r\n\r\nTo include a variable like a name in your message, you can combine strings using the `+` operator. Here's an example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nprint(\"Hi, \" + name + \"!\")\r\n```\r\n\r\nMake sure to include spaces **inside the quotes**, like `\"Hi, \"` and `\"!\"`, or the message will get squished together.",
